vectorData.altText: 22. The specific nerve branch responsible for cutaneous sensation over the dorsum of the foot, as indicated by the letter A, is the _______ _________ nerve.
That's right!  The superficial fibular nerve provides cutaneous sensation to the dorsum of the foot.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Recall that the common fibular nerve gives rise to the lateral cutaneous nerve of the calf, prior to passing laterally around the neck of the fibula     , and then bifurcating into the superficial and deep fibular nerves     . 
Recall that the superficial fibular nerve innervates the fibularis longus and brevis, and therefore controls what movement of the foot?
Recall, further, that the superficial fibular nerve emerges from the lateral compartment of the leg to provide cutaneous sensation to the dorsum of the foot. From this, you know the distribution of sensory symptoms associated with a lesion involving the superficial fibular nerve.
Clinicians may refer to these as the superficial and deep peroneal nerves.
Do you recall why it is significant that the lateral cutaneous nerve of the calf arises proximal to the common fibular nerve crossing the neck of the fibula?
